Before we started dancing, I shared my take on the oscars situation:
I feel like my whole dance upbringing and dance career, South asians have been conditioned to believe cultural styles have no technique, no form and no discipline. Classical styles such as Bharatnatyam and Kathak are not viewed with the same revere as Ballet or Jazz. We’ve been told that we have to train in so many other styles, alongside our cultural styles to “count” to “matter”. This Sunday, South Indian cinema was robbed, South Indian culture was robbed. Tollywood was robbed. India was robbed. Every Indian American who was told their dancing wasn’t technical enough watched as dancers with no ties to our culture and heritage tried to dance as us. As someone who’s only recently entered the industry, in no way am I upset this opportunity wasn’t mine. I am heartbroken I didn’t see my own up there. 

So, the night before class, I changed my entire choreography. I removed any elements of western technique I had, and celebrated pure Bollywood Indian movement. We danced with heavy hearts and our souls last night. Growing up half-breed, (as my Manglorean mother and Sindhi father call me) I was raised primarily by my Aaji. My South Indian heritage is one I strongly identify with and as kid, I was often made fun of for it. However, seeing the unity the South Asian community has this week to make sure Tollywood got the recognition it deserved, it made me so emotional🫶

I deliberately waited until class to reveal the theme for today, and here’s why. Ive realized that there’s a block between us expressing while we dance, something that prevents us from letting go and expressing the meaning of the song. So I created a little storyline. Here it goes: 
You’re alone, sitting at a pond, and in the water, you see a reflection of a younger version of yourself. The reflection comes to life, even waves back at you. If there was anything you could tell your younger self, what would it be? How would you soothe the inner child in you that was told they weren’t good/pretty/talented/strong enough? What would you say through movement? Somewhere in this dance, you lose sight of the reflection, was it just you all along? But we see at the end, the younger you has left a ball of light, you take it, you place it within your heart, and you are now unstoppable🧡.
The energy in this room was indescribable. Thank you New York for putting up with my madness. I love you. 

🎥 : @savsalud

If there was something you could say to the younger version of yourself, what would it be? 🫶🥹
TW: Bullying
Growing up, I was constantly bullied about my weight, called horrible names by my dance teachers, and, sometimes, even by members of my own family. I would constantly be denied leads or solos because of my size, and since costumes wouldn’t be made available in my size, my mom would skillfully spend nights altering them so that I could still be a part of performances. My younger self starved herself and spent hours trying to “fix how she looked.” Eighty pounds of weight loss later, the younger me had eating disorders and anxiety, but still felt like she wasn’t good enough. I was finally getting the attention I wanted, being called “beautiful” but what I wish I could tell baby Vini, was that she was beautiful this entire time. She was a star the whole time. I wish I could go back and give her the validation she so pleadingly sought from those who mocked her. I wish I could tell her that no matter where she stood on stage, her soul danced and that was what made her special. ❤️

When I made the jump in my career to do this full-time, I felt like an imposter in new spaces. For auditions, meetings, and even the classes I take to train, only a few people looked like me. It’s no secret that South Asian choreographers and artists have had to bust through many glass ceilings to get to where we are today. I created performance classes with two things in mind: instilling confidence and discipline. Sometimes, we create stories in our minds that we aren’t trained enough for certain opportunities, but in reality, we are the ones who stop ourselves from working to get there. I truly feel like the New York community is at a point where we level each other up. I mean it when I say this was truly my favorite class to date. Everyone showed up ON TIME 👏🏼 , ready to push themselves beyond their limiting beliefs. I was incredibly proud of how everyone learned and executed this routine in less than an hour. NYC, you are incredible.

Introducing our second Instructor for DESI DANCE FEST 2.0. @vinihazari will be teaching a beautiful semi classical choreography. 

Vini (Vinita) Hazari is an energetic emerging choreographer based in New York and New Jersey. With over fourteen years of dance experience, she has recently gained attention for her innovative concept videos, which specifically target mental health stigmas within the South Asian community. Prior to conceptualizing, producing, choreographing and performing in dance videos, she trained in Kathak under Guru Rachana Sarang. Kathak is a fundamental aspect of her choreography and she continues to implement it in her Semi-Classical choreography.
Prior to teaching independently, she learnt jazz and contemporary from Shiamak Davar Institute of Performing Arts and worked as a teacher with them for 3 years. Besides her training in South Asian styles of dance, Vini regularly trains in Western styles of dance as well. Under her mentor and renowned choreographer Chris Gayle, Vini trains extensively in Jazz Funk, Hip Hop Ballet, and Contemporary.

Get your tickets for this class ASAP at desidancefest.com

✨25 and Blessed✨
In our mid-twenties, birthdays feel like milestone checklists. As a kid, what I associated with presents and chocolate eventually became an evaluation of how I was doing at this thing called “life.” But not this year. This year, I’ve promised myself that I determine my own value, my own validation, and most importantly, my own happiness. Ive told myself taking a leap of faith and leaving what society would label the “stability of a 9-5” to follow my dreams would be the best decision ever. I’ve promised myself that I will do my best to make every student I encounter feel the same euphoria dance gives me. I’ve promised myself that I will constantly remind myself that I deserve to take up space. I’ve traded in checklists for happiness and the thrill of uncertainty, and I won’t look back. 

Love
Vini

Through tears, this is for you. For every parent in Gaza who has had to bury their child, carry their children to safety, or tried to shield their children from mass destruction, giving up their own lives selflessly, we see you. The world weeps with you. 

The inspiration for this piece was an incredibly heavy one. But the energy in this room was indescribable. We acknowledged what a privilege it was to be able to dance in a studio, safely and happily doing what we love most. 

I will never ever let myself take this for granted. 

New York, I love you. 

I will teach this piece one more time in New York City, in a much more intimate class setting. There are less than 10 spots left.

Introducing Vinita Hazari

Vini (Vinita) Hazari is a New York and New Jersey-based choreographer with extensive training in Kathak under Guru Rachana Sarang. Kathak remains a fundamental aspect in Vini’s Semi-Classical choreography. With five years of experience as an instructor at the Shiamak Davar Institute of Performing Arts, she is currently teaching Bollywood, Bolly Jazz Funk and Semi-Classical classes in New York City.

Happy New Year 💓 My word of this year: reconnect. 

After I lost my grandfather, I couldn’t bring myself to go back to India. Growing up, several of my summers were spent in Mumbai, and I never wanted to leave, sometimes faking sick to extend our trips🙈. But in 2016, since my last memory of Mumbai brought me so much grief, so much that I didn’t process, I wasn’t ready to go back. Something in the universe told me it was time this year. And boy, did I fall in love with Mumbai, all over again. 

Here’s to a year of rekindling old connections, sparking new ones, a year of adventures and blessings. I’m so excited to continue this journey. Thank you to each and every one of you, I am so grateful and blessed to have you on this journey with me.
